layers.

6
00:00:24,290 --> 00:00:26,750
And we will develop ordering domain layer.

7
00:00:26,750 --> 00:00:32,540
So during this section we will learn and develop tactical domain driven design patterns like entities,

8
00:00:32,540 --> 00:00:38,690
value objects, aggregates, aggregate routes, patterns for ordering entities when developing the ordering

9
00:00:38,690 --> 00:00:39,530
domain layer.

10
00:00:40,670 --> 00:00:45,980
As you know, that domain driven design has divided two types, which are the strategic and tactical

11
00:00:45,980 --> 00:00:47,090
domain driven design.

12
00:00:47,090 --> 00:00:52,580
In strategic domain driven design, we basically understand and modeling the business domain, but in

13
00:00:52,580 --> 00:00:57,830
the tactical domain driven design, we will implementation details and provides the design patterns,

14
00:00:57,830 --> 00:01:02,540
including the patterns like entities, value objects, aggregates, and so on.

15
00:01:02,780 --> 00:01:06,380
So let's understand what is the tactical domain driven design?

16
00:01:06,380 --> 00:01:12,440
Tactical domain driven design is a set of pattern and principles that help in modeling complex software

17
00:01:12,440 --> 00:01:13,220
systems.

18
00:01:13,220 --> 00:01:19,430
It focuses on the domain and domain logic, emphasizing the importance of a model that reflects the

19
00:01:19,430 --> 00:01:24,950
business and the rules, and tactical domain driven design patterns include a set of the patterns.

20
00:01:24,950 --> 00:01:29,660
These are the entities, value objects, aggregates, and aggregate rules.

21
00:01:29,930 --> 00:01:36,440
So now let's delve into some key tactical domain driven design patterns and see how they can be implemented

22
00:01:36,440 --> 00:01:37,820
in the ordering domain layer.

23
00:01:37,820 --> 00:01:41,540
In a clean architecture setup, the first one is entities.

24
00:01:41,660 --> 00:01:47,750
An entity is an object that identified by its identity rather than its attributes.

25
00:01:47,960 --> 00:01:52,730
The identity makes each entity unique even if other attributes are the same.

26
00:01:53,590 --> 00:01:59,380
Entities are used to represent objects in the system that have a distinct identity and life cycle.

27
00:01:59,380 --> 00:02:04,270
They often correspond to real world objects that need to be tracked or managed.

28
00:02:04,420 --> 00:02:07,330
As an example, we can give ordering microservices.

29
00:02:07,360 --> 00:02:09,250
An order can be an entity.

30
00:02:09,340 --> 00:02:16,630
It is unique identified by an order ID, even if the other attributes are identical to another order.

31
00:02:16,660 --> 00:02:22,420
Here you can see an example of the order implementation as an entity, and you can see the order ID,

32
00:02:22,420 --> 00:02:25,390
which makes it each entity as a unique.

33
00:02:25,420 --> 00:02:28,360
So the next item is value objects.

34
00:02:28,540 --> 00:02:34,600
A value object is an object that describes some characteristics or attributes, but carries no concept

35
00:02:34,600 --> 00:02:35,590
of the identity.

36
00:02:36,100 --> 00:02:41,170
Value objects are used to describe aspects of the domain with no conceptual identity.

37
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:46,090
They are immutable and are often used to encapsulate complex attributes.

38
00:02:46,120 --> 00:02:52,810
As an example, we can give address used in the order might be a value object, as it is important for

39
00:02:52,810 --> 00:02:55,780
the order, but doesn't define the order's identity.

40
00:02:55,810 --> 00:03:01,900
Here you can see the address value object, including street and city information belongs to the order

41
00:03:01,900 --> 00:03:05,890
entity and another item is aggregates.

42
00:03:05,980 --> 00:03:12,520
And aggregate is a cluster of domain objects, which is the entities and value objects that can be treated

43
00:03:12,520 --> 00:03:13,750
as a single unit.

44
00:03:14,140 --> 00:03:18,400
An aggregate will have one of its component be aggregate root.

45
00:03:19,060 --> 00:03:19,630
Aggregates.

46
00:03:19,630 --> 00:03:22,270
Define a boundary around related objects.

47
00:03:22,270 --> 00:03:28,570
Operations within the boundary should maintain consistency of changes to the data in the aggregate.

48
00:03:28,840 --> 00:03:35,560
As an example, order can be an aggregate containing the order items, payment details and so on, and

49
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:37,930
these will be within it of the entity.

50
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:45,280
The consistency of an order like total price calculation stock validation is maintained within the aggregate

51
00:03:45,280 --> 00:03:45,940
boundaries.

52
00:03:45,970 --> 00:03:52,840
Here you can see an example order as an aggregate and order will be managed consistency between the

53
00:03:52,840 --> 00:03:57,190
items with order items, price calculation, validation and so on.

54
00:03:57,700 --> 00:04:00,310
And the last item is aggregate roots.

55
00:04:00,580 --> 00:04:07,030
Aggregate root is the main entity is an aggregate through which external objects interact with the aggregate.

56
00:04:07,390 --> 00:04:14,860
It provides a gateway to the aggregate, ensuring that the aggregates invariants are enforced and consistency

57
00:04:14,860 --> 00:04:16,029
is maintained.

58
00:04:16,420 --> 00:04:18,310
As an example, we can give order.

59
00:04:18,310 --> 00:04:21,970
Aggregate order itself can be the aggregate root.

60
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:26,560
External object would interact with the order to effect change within the aggregate.

61
00:04:26,590 --> 00:04:30,490
We can see example code into aggregate root of the order.

62
00:04:31,530 --> 00:04:34,980
So we can apply all these concepts in the ordering domain layer.

63
00:04:34,980 --> 00:04:40,950
When developing the ordering domain layer in a clean architecture setup, these concepts help in creating

64
00:04:40,950 --> 00:04:44,670
a rich domain model that encapsulates business logic and rules.

65
00:04:44,850 --> 00:04:50,520
Entities and value objects define the nature of the data and their relationships, while aggregates

66
00:04:50,520 --> 00:04:55,440
and aggregate rules organize the model to ensure integrity and consistency.

